;Notes
<references group="note" />

In all, 76 nations have [[National team appearances in the FIFA World Cup|played in at least one World Cup]].<ref name="successor">FIFA considers that the national team of [[Russia national football team|Russia]] succeeds the [[Soviet Union national football team|USSR]], the national team of  [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] succeeds the [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]]/[[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|Serbia and Montenegro]], and the national team of [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] succeeds the [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]]. ({{cite web |url=http://www.fifa.com/associations/association=rus/index.html |title=Russia |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association}}; {{cite web |url=http://www.fifa.com/associations/association=srb/index.html |title=Serbia |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association}}; {{cite web |url=http://www.fifa.com/associations/association=cze/index.html |title=Czech Republic |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association}}).</ref> Of these, eight national teams have won the World Cup, and they have added [[Star (football badge)|stars to their badges]], with each star representing a World Cup victory. (Uruguay, however, choose to display four stars on their badge, representing their two gold medals at the 1924 and 1928 Summer Olympics and their two World Cup titles in 1930 and 1950.)

With five titles, <!--For consistency, British English is used throughout the article, which treats teams as plural nouns, e.g., "Brazil are" instead of "Brazil is".-->Brazil are the most successful World Cup team and also the only nation to have [[National team appearances in the FIFA World Cup#Ranking of teams by number of appearances|played in every World Cup]] (19) to date,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fifa.com/associations/association=bra/index.html |title=Brazil |publisher=F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association |work=FIFA.com}}</ref> and they will host the 20th in 2014. Italy (1934 and 1938) and Brazil (1958 and 1962) are the only nations to have won consecutive titles. West Germany (1982<U+2013>1990) and Brazil (1994<U+2013>2002) are the only nations to appear in three consecutive World Cup finals. Germany have made the most top-four finishes, with twelve, while sharing the record of most top-two finishes with Brazil, with seven.

