===Best performances by continental zones===
{{See also|National team appearances in the FIFA World Cup#Results by confederation|l1=FIFA World Cup results by confederation}}
To date, the final of the World Cup has only been contested by [[UEFA|European]] and [[CONMEBOL|South American]] teams. European nations have won ten titles; South American teams have won nine. Only two teams from outside these two continents have ever reached the semi-finals of the competition: [[United States men's national soccer team|USA]] ([[CONCACAF|North, Central America and Caribbean]]) in 1930 and [[Korea Republic national football team|Korea Republic]] ([[Asian Football Confederation|Asia]]) who reached the semis in 2002. The best result of an [[Confederation of African Football|African]] team is reaching the quarter-finals: [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] in 1990, [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] in 2002 and [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] in 2010. Only one [[Oceania Football Confederation|Oceanian]] qualifier, [[Australia national association football team|Australia]] in 2006, has advanced to the second round.<ref>Australia's qualification in 2006 was through the Oceanian zone as they were a member of the [[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]] member during qualifying. However, on 1 January 2006, they left the Oceania Football Confederation and joined the [[Asian Football Confederation]].</ref> 

[[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], and [[Spain national football team|Spain]] are the only teams to win a World Cup outside their continental confederation; Brazil came out victorious in [[UEFA|Europe]] ([[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]]), [[CONCACAF|North America]] ([[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]] and [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]]) and [[Asian Football Confederation|Asia]] ([[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]]), Argentina won a North American World Cup in [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]], while Spain won the only African World Cup in [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]]. Only on three occasions have consecutive World Cups been won by teams from the same continent&nbsp;<U+2013> [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and Brazil successfully defended their titles in 1938 and 1962 respectively, while Spain's 2010 triumph followed Italy's in 2006.

==Awards==
{{Main|FIFA World Cup awards}}
At the end of each World Cup, awards are presented to the players and teams for accomplishments other than their final team positions in the tournament. There are currently six awards:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/ip-301_03a_fwc-awards_22643.pdf |title=FIFA World Cup awards |publisher=F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association |work=FIFA.com |accessdate=5 March 2009}}</ref>
*The ''[[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Golden Ball]]'' for the best player, determined by a vote of media members (first awarded in 1982); the ''Silver Ball'' and the ''Bronze Ball'' are awarded to the players finishing second and third in the voting respectively;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soccerway.com/news/2006/July/10/golden-ball-for-zinedine-zidane/ |title=Golden Ball for Zinedine Zidane |work=Soccerway |date=10 July 2006 |accessdate=31 December 2007}}</ref>
*The ''[[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Boot|Golden Boot]]'' (sometimes called the ''Golden Shoe'') for the top goalscorer (first awarded in 1982, but retrospectively applied to all tournaments from 1930); most recently, the ''Silver Boot'' and the ''Bronze Boot'' have been awarded to the second and third top goalscorers respectively;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/awards/golden/award=gsa/idcup=17/pastcupawards.html |title=adidas Golden Shoe <U+2013> FIFA World Cup Final |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association |accessdate=4 March 2009}}</ref>
*The ''[[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Glove|Golden Glove Award]]'' (formerly the ''Yashin Award'') for the best [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], decided by the FIFA Technical Study Group (first awarded in 1994);<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/team_pages/germany/newsid_2075000/2075695.stm |title=Kahn named top keeper |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 June 2002 |accessdate=31 December 2007}}</ref>
*The ''[[FIFA World Cup awards#Best Young Player Award|Best Young Player Award]]'' for the best player aged 21 or younger at the start of the calendar year, decided by the FIFA Technical Study Group (first awarded in 2006).<ref name="RSSSF FIFA awards" />
*The ''[[FIFA World Cup awards#FIFA Fair Play Trophy|FIFA Fair Play Trophy]]'' for the team with the best record of [[sportsmanship|fair play]], according to the points system and criteria established by the FIFA Fair Play Committee (first awarded in 1978);<ref name="RSSSF FIFA awards">{{cite web |first=Jos<U+00E9> Luis |last=Pierrend |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-awards.html |title=FIFA Awards |publisher=rec.sport.soccer Statistics Foundation |date=18 May 2007 |accessdate=8 January 2008}}</ref>
*The ''[[FIFA World Cup awards#Most Entertaining Team|Most Entertaining Team]]'' for the team that has entertained the public the most during the World Cup, determined by a poll of the general public (first awarded in 1994);<ref name="RSSSF FIFA awards" />
An ''[[FIFA World Cup awards#All-Star Team|All-Star Team]]'' consisting of the best players of the tournament has also been announced for each tournament since 1998.

==Records and statistics==
{{Main|FIFA World Cup records}}
Two players share the record for [[List of players who have appeared in multiple FIFA World Cups|playing in the most World Cups]]; [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]]'s [[Antonio Carbajal]] (1950<U+2013>1966) and [[Germany national football team|Germany]]'s [[Lothar Matth<U+00E4>us]] (1982<U+2013>1998) both played in five tournaments.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C00EFD8103AF933A25752C1A96F958260 |title=Matthaus Is the Latest MetroStars Savior |work=New York Times |last=Yannis |first=Alex |date=10 November 1999 |accessdate=23 December 2007}}</ref> Matth<U+00E4>us has played the most World Cup matches overall, with 25 appearances.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/world/2002/world_cup/hof/matthaeus/ |title=World Cup Hall of Fame: Lothar Matthaeus |publisher=CNN |accessdate=23 December 2007}}</ref> [[Germany national football team|West Germany]]'s [[Franz Beckenbauer]] (1966<U+2013>1974) is the only player to be named to three Finals [[FIFA World Cup awards#All-Star Team|All-Star Teams]].

In November 2007, FIFA announced that all members of World Cup-winning squads between 1930 and 1974 were to be retroactively awarded winners' medals.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=484715&cc=4716 |title=122 forgotten heroes get World Cup medals |work=ESPNSoccernet.com |publisher=ESPN |date=25 November 2007}}</ref> This made [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]'s [[Pel<U+00E9>]] the only player to have won three World Cup winners' medals (1958, 1962, and 1970, although he did not play in the 1962 final due to injury),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/classic/bio/news/story?page=Pele |title=Pele, King of Futbol |publisher=ESPN |last=Kirby |first=Gentry |date=5 July 2006 |accessdate=23 December 2007}}</ref> with [[List of players who have won multiple FIFA World Cups|20 other players who have won two winners' medals]]. Six players have collected all three types of World Cup medals (winners', runner- ups', and third-place); five players were from [[Germany national football team|West Germany]]'s squad of 1966<U+2013>1974 including [[Franz Beckenbauer]], and the most recent has been Italy's [[Franco Baresi]] (1982, 1990, 1994).

The [[List of FIFA World Cup goalscorers#Overall top goalscorers|overall top goalscorer in World Cups]] is Brazil's [[Ronaldo]], scorer of 15 goals (1998<U+2013>2006). Germany's [[Miroslav Klose]] (2002<U+2013>2010) and West Germany's [[Gerd M<U+00FC>ller]] (1970<U+2013>1974) are second, with 14 goals.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/teams/brazil/5112982.stm |title=Ronaldo's riposte |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 June 2006 |last=Chowdhury |first=Saj |accessdate=23 December 2007}}</ref> The fourth placed goalscorer, [[France national football team|France]]'s [[Just Fontaine]], holds the record for the most goals scored in a single World Cup; all his 13 goals were scored in the 1958 tournament.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/team_pages/france/newsid_1752000/1752740.stm |title=Goal machine was Just superb |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 April 2002 |accessdate=23 December 2007}}</ref>

Brazil's [[M<U+00E1>rio Zagallo]] and West Germany's [[Franz Beckenbauer]] are the only people to date to win the World Cup as both player and head coach. Zagallo won in 1958 and 1962 as a player and in 1970 as head coach.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Rob |date=11 March 1998 |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/1998/03/11/soccer.t_7.php |title=No Alternative to Victory for National Coach : 150 Million Brazilians Keep Heat on Zagalo |work=International Herald Tribune |accessdate=31 December 2007 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080226063509/http://www.iht.com/articles/1998/03/11/soccer.t_7.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 26 February 2008}}</ref> Beckenbauer won in 1974 as captain and in 1990 as head coach.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/archive/worldcup/editorial/legends_beckenbauer.html |title=World Cup Legends <U+2013> Franz Beckenbauer |work=ESPNSoccernet.com |publisher=ESPN |last=Brewin |first=John |date=21 December 2007 |accessdate=31 December 2007}}</ref> [[Italy national football team|Italy]]'s [[Vittorio Pozzo]] is the only head coach to ever win two World Cups (1934 and 1938).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/worldcup2006/history/events/1938.html |title=1938 France |publisher=CBC |accessdate=31 December 2007}}</ref> All World Cup winning head coaches were natives of the country they coached to victory.

Among the national teams, Germany have played the most World Cup matches, with 99,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/news/newsid=1269182/index.html |title=Germany move ahead of Brazil |publisher=F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association |work=FIFA.com |date=6 July 2010 |accessdate=6 July 2010}}</ref> while Brazil have scored the most World Cup goals, with 210.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/NATIONS/maraton.html |title=Planet World Cup <U+2013> All time table |publisher=Planet World Cup |accessdate=26 January 2008}}</ref> The two teams have played each other only once in the World Cup, in the [[2002 FIFA World Cup Final|2002 final]].
